{{Infobox football biography | playername = SÅta Hirayama | image = [[File:Sota Hiroyama cropped.jpg|150px]] | fullname = SÅta Hirayama | dateofbirth = {{Birth date and age|1985|6|6|df=yes}} | cityofbirth = [[KitakyÅ«shÅ«]] | countryofbirth = [[Japan]] | height = {{height|m=1.92}} | position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]] | currentclub = [[F.C. Tokyo]] | clubnumber = 13 | youthyears1 = 2001â2003 | youthyears2 = 2004â2005 | youthclubs1 = Kunimi High School | youthclubs2 = [[Tsukuba University]] | years1 = 2005â2006 | years2 = 2006â | clubs1 = [[Heracles Almelo]] | clubs2 = [[F.C. Tokyo]] | caps1 = 32 | goals1 = 8 | caps2 = 106 | goals2 = 20 | nationalyears1 = 2003â2005 | nationalyears2 = 2004â2007 | nationalyears3 = 2010 | nationalteam1 = [[Japan national under-20 football team|Japan U-20]] | nationalteam2 = [[Japan national under-23 football team|Japan U-23]] | nationalteam3 = [[Japan national football team|Japan]] | nationalcaps1 = ? | nationalcaps2 = ? | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 11 | nationalgoals2 = 3 | nationalgoals3 = 3 | pcupdate = 1 January 2011 | ntupdate = 1 January 2011 }} [[File:Sota Hirayama - top.jpg|thumb|250px|Hirayama for FC Tokyo]] {{nihongo|'''SÅta Hirayama'''|å¹³å±± ç¸å¤ª|Hirayama SÅta|extra=born 6 June 1985 in [[KitakyÅ«shÅ«]], [[Fukuoka Prefecture]], [[Japan]]}}, is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[association football|footballer]] who currently plays for [[F.C. Tokyo|FC Tokyo]]. He has represented [[Japan national football team|Japan]]'s U-20 team at the [[2003 FIFA World Youth Championship|2003]] and [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]], and the U-23 team at the [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Olympics]].
==Career== As a teenager, Hirayama attended Kunimi High School in [[Nagasaki Prefecture]]. There, he won the [[All Japan High School Soccer Tournament]] all three years at the school, leading the tournament in scoring in 2002 and 2003. In 2003, he played in the U-20 [[FIFA Youth Championship]] as a 17-year-old and scored two goals, including the game winner against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] to put Japan through to the knockout stage.<ref name="playertowatch"> {{cite news |url=http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/060130/1/5yki.html |title=Player to Watch: Hirayama hopes for Japan chance |publisher=FIFAworldcup.com |date=2006-01-30 |accessdate=2006-07-20 }} </ref>
After graduation in 2004, he enrolled at [[Tsukuba University]] instead of joining a professional club. That summer, Hirayama played in the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens and the following year, played in his second FIFA World Youth Championship.
In July 2005, Hirayama joined the [[Eredivisie]] club [[Feyenoord]] on trial and a week later, he joined another Dutch side, the newly promoted [[Heracles Almelo]].<ref> {{cite news |url=http://www.crisscross.com/jp/news/345705 |title=Hirayama to join Dutch club Heracles |publisher=Crisscross Japan |date=2006-08-08 |accessdate=2006-07-20 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}} </ref> He made his professional debut with Heracles on August 20, 2005 against [[ADO Den Haag]], playing 15 minutes and scoring 2 goals.<ref> {{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=187812&cc=5901 |title=ADO Den Haag 1-2 SC Heracles Almelo |publisher=ESPNsoccernet |date=2005-08-20 |accessdate=2006-07-20 }}</ref> He finished the 2005-2006 season with 31 appearances and 8 goals.
Although both Japan's senior side manager [[Zico]] and [[Japan Football Association]] chairman Saburo Kawabuchi praised Hirayama's progress with Heracles, he was not called up to [[Japan national football team|Japan's squad]] for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]].
On September 4, 2006, after the transfer period ended Heracles Almelo announced that Hirayama left the club by mutual consent and after being released he returned to Japan to finish his study.<ref> {{cite news |url=http://www.heracles.nl/b9032c59-1854-4285-a3a2-b1c0446f321f.aspx?newsId=1945 |title=Sota Hirayama verlaat Heracles Almelo |publisher=HeraclesAlmelo.nl |date=2006-09-04 |accessdate=2006-09-04 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Only a few days later he signed a contract with [[FC Tokyo]] without informing Heracles as a free agent, while he still had a contract until 2008 before his release. Heracles appealed to this unexpected move by Hirayama.<ref> {{cite news |url=http://www.nos.nl/nos/artikelen/2006/09/art000001C6D0EF6C0D834D.html |title=Hirayama nog niet van Heracles af |publisher=NOS.nl |date=2006-09-12 |accessdate=2006-09-12 }}</ref>
==International career== Hirayama has played for younger Japanese national teams including their U/20's and U/23's team. His debut for the [[Japan national football team|senior team]] came on January 6, 2010 in a [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]] qualifier against [[Yemen national football team|Yemen]], and would be a game he would never forget. After 30 minutes, Japan were down 2-0, but Hirayama scored a [[hat trick]] to help Japan to a 3-2 victory. It was the first time in 80 years and the second time overall for a Japan player to score three goals on his debut. Takeo Wakabayashi last managed that in 1930.<ref>[http://www.jfa.or.jp/eng/topics/2010/8.html Japan rally past Yemen, qualify for 2011 Asian Cup]</ref>
